revision.text:
Sir '''Joseph Muter''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|KCH}} (1777{{snd}}23{{nbsp}}October 1840) was a [[British Army]] officer who fought in the [[Peninsular War]] at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] on 18{{nbsp}}June 1815.

==Early life and career==
Born the youngest son of William Muter of Annfield in [[Fifeshire]] and Janet, née Stratton of Kirkside in [[Kincardineshire]],{{sfn|Bromley|Bromley|2015|page=111}}   he was educated at the [[University of Edinburgh]] where his class mates included [[James Abercromby, 1st Baron Dunfermline|James Abercromby]], later [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]].<ref name=Dundee>{{cite news |title=Professor Dalziel's Class in 1791 |work=Dundee Courier |date=21 October 1864 |accessdate=4 October 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000162/18641021/005/0003| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref name=Standard>{{cite news |title=Lord Broughham and his Education in Edinburgh |work=London Evening Standard] |date=6 November 1857 |accessdate=4 October 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000183/18571106/034/0006| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref>

Muter joined the [[British Army]] as a [[cornet (rank)|cornet]] in the [[2nd Dragoon Guards]] in December 1794.{{sfn|Bromley|Bromley|2015|page=111}} 
On 5{{nbsp}}September 1801 he was promoted from captain to major [[Purchase of commissions in the British army|by purchase]] in the [[13th Light Dragoons]].<ref>{{cite news |title=War Office Sept. 5 |work=Morning Post |date=7 September 1801 |accessdate=4 October 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000175/18010907/010/0004| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> then on 6{{nbsp}}May 1808 he transferred in the same rank to the [[23rd Light Dragoons]].<ref>{{cite news |title=From the London Gazette |work=Belfast Commercial Chronicle |date=14 May 1808 |accessdate=4 October 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001287/18080514/051/0004| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> He later saw service in the [[Peninsular War]] with the [[13th Light Dragoons]] and was present at the battles of [[Battle of Campo Maior|Campo Mayor]], [[Battle of Albuera|Albuera]] [[Battle of Usagre|Usagre]] [[Battle of Arroyo dos Molinos|Arroyo de Molinos]] and [[Battle of Alba de Tormes|Alba de Tormes]].{{sfn|Bromley|Bromley|2015|page=111}}

==Waterloo==
At the [[Battle of Waterloo]] and by then a Lieutenant-Colonel, Muter commanded the [[6th (Inniskilling) Dragoons|6th Inniskilling (Irish) Regiment of Dragoons]].
During the battle, in response to the French Infantry assault on [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Wellington]]'s left centre, the Union Brigade moved forward. Unobserved until late in their advance, they caught the French by surprise and took around 1,000 prisoners, despite the two British heavy cavalry brigades losing half their numbers at the hands of the French Lancers and [[Cuirassier]]s.<ref name=NAM>{{cite web|title=Letter describing Waterloo by Colonel Joseph Muter|publisher=200 Objects of Waterloo, [[National Army Museum]]|url=http://www.nam.ac.uk/waterloo200/200-object/letter-written-by-colonel-joseph-muter-following-the-battle-of-waterloo/|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>

Following the death of Major-General Sir [[William Ponsonby (British Army officer)|William Ponsonby]] command of the [[2nd Cavalry Brigade (United Kingdom)|2nd Union Cavalry Brigade]] devolved upon Muter.{{sfn|Dalton|1904|page=62}}

At around 6pm, after [[La Haye Sainte]] farm had fallen to the French, Muter was struck by a musket ball in the right wrist. The injury quickly became infected with pieces of glove and pus oozing from the wound although he subsequently recovered without the need for amputation.<ref name=NAM />

==Later life==
After Waterloo he was awarded the Russian [[Order of St. Vladimir]] and served in Ireland in 1819. He was made a [[baronet]] and colonel of the [[8th Light Dragoons]] on 24{{nbsp}}August 1839 and Colonel of the 6th Inniskilling (Irish) Regiment of Dragoons on 30{{nbsp}}April 1840.{{sfn|Bromley|Bromley|2015|page=111}}
Some time around 1816 he changed his surname to Straton after inheriting a property belonging to his aunt in Kirkside, {{convert|3|mile}} north of [[Montrose, Angus|Montrose]] in Scotland. Muter left a legacy of around £70,000 (about £6.2 million at 2015 values) to the University of Edinburgh.{{sfn|Dalton|1904|page=62}} He was later described as one of the greatest benefactors of the university.<ref name=Standard />

==Death==
Muter died in London on 23{{nbsp}}October 1840 at the age of 63 and is buried in the family plot in Nether Kirkyard, [[St Cyrus]], near Montrose where there is monument with a dedication to him.{{sfn|Bromley|Bromley|2015|page=111}}

